Write a Java program that demonstrates the difference between pre-increment and post-increment operators. Create a variable count and initialize it with a value of 5. Use both pre-increment and post-increment operators to increment the value of count. Print the value of count before and after each increment operation.

Write a Java program to calculate the sum of two numbers using pre-decrement and post-decrement operators. Create two variables num1 and num2 and initialize them with any integer values. Use pre-decrement and post-decrement operators to decrement the values of num1 and num2 respectively, and store the decremented values in new variables. Finally, calculate the sum of the decremented values and print the result.

Write a Java program that demonstrates the concept of unary minus (-) operator. Create a variable value and assign it a positive integer value. Use the unary minus operator to obtain the negative value of value and store it in a new variable. Print both the original and negated values of value.

Write a Java program to swap the values of two variables without using a temporary variable. Create two variables a and b and assign them any integer values. Use the pre-increment and pre-decrement operators to swap the values of a and b. Print the values of a and b before and after the swap.    
    